        conseils: "For your Lyon — Geneva journey, remember to bring a valid passport or ID card. Although Switzerland is part of the Schengen area, French and Swiss customs regularly carry out checks at Bardonnex. If carrying goods or gifts of significant value, check Swiss customs allowances (CHF 300 per person). Avoid Monday morning and Friday evening departures, peak times for cross-border workers on the A40. If heading to international organisations (UN, WHO, ICRC), specify the exact address as the Nations district is vast and access points vary. For travellers going to Geneva-Cointrin airport, provide your flight time: your driver will adjust departure for arrival 2h before take-off. In winter, the Jura route can be snowy but the A40 is well maintained and our vehicles are equipped accordingly. The Swiss franc (CHF) is the local currency in Geneva, but euros are widely accepted.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The TGV Lyria Lyon Part-Dieu — Geneva Cornavin takes about 1h50 for a ticket of €35 to €79 depending on the period. BlaBlaCar offers rides between €15 and €25 per passenger. By car, budget €18 for fuel, €19.80 for French tolls and CHF 40 (~€38) for the annual Swiss motorway vignette (mandatory), totalling at least €76. The TaxiNeo taxi at €210 — €270 for 1 to 4 passengers offers international door-to-door service without the hassle of the Swiss vignette, Geneva parking (among the most expensive in Europe) or station connections. For 3 or 4 travellers, the cost per person (€52 to €90) is very competitive against the TGV Lyria, especially when adding a Geneva taxi to reach the final destination from Cornavin station.",
